   "source": [
    "# Continuous $\varepsilon$-Sinkhorn flow\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook illustrates the continuous-time potential flow obtained from the high-resolution scaling of Sinkhorn iterations studied by Berman.  One lets the grid resolution $k$ grow while setting the entropic temperature to $\\epsilon=k^{-1}$, and observes the scaled log-Sinkhorn iterates at continuous time $t=m/k$.  The vanishing-temperature limit is a parabolic Monge--Ampere equation for a gauge-fixed potential $u_t$,\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\partial_t u_t(x)\n",
    "= \\log \\det(I+\\nabla^2 u_t(x))\n",
    "  -G(x+\\nabla u_t(x))+F(x)-\\bar r_t,\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $\\alpha=e^{-F}dx$ and $\\beta=e^{-G}dx$ are normalized densities on the unit-volume periodic domain.  The scalar $\\bar r_t$ fixes the additive gauge of the potential.  In one dimension the determinant becomes $1+u_t''$, and the flow is easy to visualize as curves evolving from the zero initialization.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "fd4cdccd",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The two examples below are deliberately smooth.  This keeps the numerical solution inside the convexity regime $1+u''>0$ and makes the picture an illustration of the flow rather than a stress test of a PDE solver."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "286daada",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2026-06-18T13:35:28.581703Z",
